<DocsLayout title="Prompting basics" currentSlug="ai/prompting">
  <h1>Prompting basics</h1>
  <p>
    For agentic coding work specifically (not just chat), the prompt that
    matters most isn't the first message -- it's the ongoing context you
    give the agent as it works: what files matter, what constraints apply,
    and what "done" looks like.
  </p>

  <h2>Be concrete about the goal</h2>
  <p>
    "Fix the bug" gives an agent nothing to verify against. "Fix the bug
    where X happens when Y, confirmed by running Z" gives it a repro and a
    pass/fail check. Agents do better with a falsifiable target than with
    a vague direction, for the same reason people do.
  </p>

  <h2>Say what NOT to do</h2>
  <p>
    Scope is often the actual failure mode -- an agent asked to fix one
    thing refactors three others along the way. Explicit constraints
    ("don't touch the auth module", "no new dependencies") cut down on
    that more reliably than hoping the model infers your intent.
  </p>

  <h2>Give it a way to check its own work</h2>
  <p>
    If there's a test suite, a type checker, or a build step, say so and
    expect the agent to run it. An agent that can verify its own output
    catches its own mistakes; one that can't just reports success and
    moves on.
  </p>

  <h2>Context beats cleverness</h2>
  <p>
    A model told "here are the three files this touches and here's why
    they're structured this way" outperforms one given a cleverly-worded
    one-liner and no context. Point it at the relevant code and docs
    before asking it to write more code.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
